05127nam a22008775i 9781487515324DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192018onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875153247 a10.3138/97814875153242doi  a(DE-B1597)515745  a(OCoLC)1076269182  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aNX556.A1bG47 2018eb 7aART0151002bisacsh04a700.9472231 aGérin, Annie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDevastation and Laughter :bSatire, Power, and Culture in the Early Soviet State (1920s–1930s) /cAnnie Gérin. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tInvocation by Laughter -- tTable of Contents -- tIllustrations -- tNote on Transliteration, Translation, and Dates -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Devastation and Laughter -- tChapter One. Anatoly Lunacharsky and the Power of Laughter -- tChapter Two. Soviet Satirical Print Culture: A Serious Affair -- tChapter Three. Laughter in the Ring, in the Street, and on Stage: The Emergence of a Satirical Scene -- tChapter Four. Laughter on the Silver Screen: From Satire to Optimistic Comedy -- tChapter Five. The Strategies and Targets of Satire -- tChapter Six. The Rhetorics of Satire and Socialist Realism -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Devastation and Laughter, Annie Gérin explores the use of satire in the visual arts, the circus, theatre, and cinema under Lenin and Stalin. Gérin traces the rise and decline of the genre and argues that the use of satire in official Soviet art and propaganda was neither marginal nor un-theorized. The author sheds light on the theoretical texts written in the 1920s and 1930s by Anatoly Lunacharsky, the Soviet Commissar of Enlightenment, and the impact his writings had on satirists. While the Avant-Garde and Socialist Realism were necessarily forward-looking and utopian, satire afforded artists the means to examine critically past and present subjects, themes, and practice. Devastation and Laughter is the first work to bring Soviet theoretical writings on the use of satire to the attention of scholars outside of Russia. By introducing important bodies of work that have largely been overlooked in the fields of art history, film and theatre history, Annie Gérin provides a nuanced and alternative reading of early Soviet art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aArt and statezSoviet Union. 0aArts, Soviet. 0aLaughterzSoviet Union. 0aSatire in art. 0aSatire, Soviet. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh  aAnatoly Lunacharsky.  aSatire.  aSoviet.  aart.  acinema.  acircus.  atheatre.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2019z9783110605785oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751532440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487515324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487515324.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-061001-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb20